column306: Depending on how much of a loss I felt if I played or not (losing only 5 compared to possibility winning 10 for example).  I didn't play if there was a zero.
If difference between lower amount and payoff was less than difference between higher amount and payoff  I just went for the sure payoff.
Looked to see if I would gain a significant amount of points if I did play compared to the sure payoff.
I tried to guess the probability that the other player would play or not  according to his quantity of points.
Never taking risks on offers that seemed too low in my favor.
Try to think of  what decisions will be made by the partner.

-If A/C is guaranteed  and is higher than sure payoff  pick yes. | -If A/C is guaranteed  and is lower than sure payoff  pick no. | -If state is unknown  determine what other player would pick if they knew that A/C was guaranteed.  Generally on an A or B or a B or C  one state is higher than sure payoff and the other is lower.  If the higher state is A/C and the other player would pick yes  pick yes.  If the higher state is under A/C and the other player would pick no  pick no (because in this case  the other player would only pick yes for B  which would make me lose money).  If the higher state for me is B  try to figure out what I would pick if I were the other player and I also did not know the state.  Then choose yes or no accordingly.

If I knew the exact state I was in and if it was higher than the sure payoff  I would play the game.  If it was lower than the sure payoff  I would not play.  If I had a choice between two states  I would look at the other players points and look at the possible payouts.  If there were more favorable outcomes than bad  I would play.
If I knew the state for sure I would bet depending on the amount of the state  if not I just played whatever seemed the most secure.
i tried to fuigure out what the pther player had... and used the numbers to decided whether I would play the game or not

I looked at the "sure payoff" box and then looked at the info I was given.  If I lost only a few points  and gained a lot of points then I played the game.  If I looked are the "sure payoff" box and knew for sure that we were in State C  and the amount of points were less than the "sure payoff" then I wouldn't play the game.  Also  if I knew that we were in state A or B  and I wouldn't lose too many points (less than 5) and I saw that the other person's points were close so that we would both benefit (potentially) then I played the game.
consider my intersts first  and then consider intersts of others.

I assumed if someone knew the answer and their number was small  I would click play assuming they wouldn't if it was small.  This allowed me to play the middle number if I was given two choices.  People did not follow this logic as many people (I assume) made their choices off whether the average of the two numbers was greater than the sure payoff.  I lost money because of my assumptions.
